<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-419-786  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 419 786.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  May 1990 v7 n5 p83(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Many paths to X window programming. (includes related article onGUI programming)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Southerton, Alan.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A new type of software called user interface management systems(UIMS) is being used to relate various graphical user interfaces(GUIs) to their X Windows systems without having to rely onskilled C programmers.andP;  Software vendors considering X Windowsdevelopment have a choice between the UIMS approach and that ofthe proprietary toolkit.andP;  The toolkit method needs theparticipation of C programmers while the UIMS has the disadvantageof lacking smooth migration to other windowing systems such asMacintosh or Microsoft Windows.andP;  UIMS packages allow theprogrammer to develop an end-user interface quickly and then linkit to the application code.andP;  The software is either of the WYSIWYGor scripting variety.andP;  UIMS speeds the programming cycle andcodifies style for programmers.andP;  The great appeal of UIMS is theease of conversion of C programs to GUI programs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     UNIXComputer GraphicsGraphical User InterfaceIntegrated SoftwareC Programming LanguageX Windows (Standard)Program Development Tools.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>